    "justification": "Four conjuncts (one fewer than the groove_width fixture because the NCO magnitude is not load-bearing here): (1)+(2) opposite signs — negative for CO, positive for NCO — exactly the sign-flip pattern; (3) |CO partial r| > 0.1 ensures the CO side is above the noise floor; (4) Steiger Z p < 0.01 confirms the CO vs NCO difference is significant. The NCO magnitude (0.064) is too small to test against 0.1, so we do not constrain it; the claim is explicitly 'asymmetric sign-flip, CO-dominated' for curvature.",
    "failure_mode": "If s_partial_r_curv_co flipped sign (became positive like groove_width), the mechanism claim — curvature DISfavors CO resolution, opposite to groove width — collapses. The sign of s_partial_r_curv_nco alone is not load-bearing due to magnitude < 0.1."
  },
  "conclusion": {
    "assertion": "After GC residualization, mean curvature at 1 Mb autosomal resolution has a negative partial Spearman correlation with crossover rate (-0.238) and a weakly positive partial correlation with non-crossover rate (+0.064); the difference is significant by Steiger's Z. Curvature disfavors crossover resolution — the opposite mechanical direction from groove width — consistent with distinct strand-invasion physics for CO vs NCO outcomes.",
